It's a life size Magnemite! I'm a huge fan of Pokémon and I was looking for something that's a relatively simple shape to demonstrate my modeling process for an upcoming video. So Magnemite was perfect. Then I drew some inspiration from The 3D Printing Nerd to make him big!

This didn't take too long to model. It was round 3 hours when all was ready to print. This model is broken up into a few easier to print parts. The main sphere is in 2 parts with the eye on one side and the back being just a half-sphere. Then there are 2 magnets with a magnet pin to allow the magnets to rotate freely in the socket to provide a little more accuracy to the character. Then there are 3 screws that will just fit in the corresponding holes on the model. This model can be pretty easily scaled as well. The smaller version was just scaled down from the big one.

The big version was printed on my Robo3D in PLA and it took close to 40 hours to print everything. The smaller version was printed on my Da Vinci 1.0 Pro in ABS and took about 14 hours to print.

After that my wife attempted to walk me through her painting/post-processing techniques. The smaller one was finished by me, as you can probably tell by the quality. And the bigger one was finished beautifully by my wife. I will have a few videos coming shortly that completely show these processes from start to finish.

Boom Block V1

German below

Pyrotechnic firing base for theatre bang to the installation

This launching platform for stage pyrotechnics supports the simulation of shoots in theater, film and television. The launching base of PLA Or metal / steel material (80 x 40 x 20 mm) is simply equipped with a theater bang or theater flash (max. 50 x 15 x 15 mm). Behind the Scenes Screwed, in which a decorative hole was previously worked in. Which is covered by a film and varnish on vehicles or by a wall wallpaper. By the ignition of the effect the hole travels up and the shot hole comes to the fore.

The launching base is intended for small productions for which not much money is available or a purchase from steel is not worth it. This project is still in development phase, so make sure you keep the rest of the information before you create this object with your 3D printer.

Safety notes
Printing and using is at your own risk and should only be left to experienced professionals. In case of intended use a test must be carried out beforehand. Always download the latest STL file version.

Pyrotechnische Abschussbasis für Theaterknall zum Einbau

Diese Abschussbasis für Bühnenpyrotechnik unterstützt die Simulation von Geschosseinschlägen in Kulissen für Theater, Film und Fernsehen. Die Abschussbasis aus PLA oder Metall / Stahl Material (80 x 40 x 20 mm) wird einfach mit einem Theaterknall oder Theaterblitz (max. 50 x 15 x 15 mm) bestückt. Hinter der Kulisse Angeschraubt, in der vorher ein Dekoratives Loch eingearbeitet wurde. Welches durch etwa einer Folie und Lack bei Fahrzeugen oder durch eine Wandtapete verdeckt wird. Durch die Zündung des Effekts reist das Loch auf und es kommt das Einschussloch zum Vorschein.

Die Abschussbasis ist für kleine Produktionen gedacht, für die nicht so viel Geld zur Verfügung steht oder eine Anschaffung aus Stahl nicht Lohnenswert ist. Dieses Projekt ist noch in Entwicklungsphase, daher beachten Sie unbedingt die übrigen Informationen, bevor Sie dieses Objekt mit ihrem 3D Drucker herstellen.

Sicherheitshinweise
Das Ausdrucken und die Verwendung geschieht auf eigene Gefahr und sollte nur erfahrenen Profis überlassen werden. Bei beabsichtigter Verwendung ist vorher eine Erprobung durch zu führen. Laden Sie immer die Aktuellste STL Datei Version.

description.text:
Hands On Search Web site

This is an attempt to design as compact as possible 3 axis brushless gimbal for SJCAM and gopro cameras.

Gimbal is designed with RCTimer GBM2804 motors in mind and targets (with the current frame mount) a flamewheel like frame with 37mm spacing between top and bottom plates.

To keep the gimbal as compact as possible the rev around Z axis is quite limited but it should be enough to smooth out yaw movements.

I did a test print and setup - with SJ4000 there's a problem with balance (should be ok now - need to reprint) on the roll axis with the current version. Untill the pitch arm is updated you'll need to either apply a small counterweight on the camera side.

Other than that - works great :) (see it here: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=gHf7ikSdP_4 , https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=tePknWLL-Ks)
Yaw is approx +-20 deg.

If you want a 2 axis skipping yaw/roll arm should do the trick :)

TODO:

  • improve balance
  • work on the frame mounting options
  • think more about cable management
  • a new version for GoPro session or SJ M10 - even more compact?

title: Printed case for IGNAS Nixie Clock

description.text: After purchasing an IGNAS Nixie Clock kit on eBay I decided to design a printable case to enclose the PCB and also keep the high voltage safely out of reach. This case design should be adaptable for similar Nixie Clock designs. OpenSCAD source is supplied so it can be customised.

nixiecaseall.stl contains all the parts required for the case. It can be printed as a single plate on a Prusa Mendel or similar 3d printer. I printed with PLA but ABS and other materials should be possible. If using ABS bear in mind that it tends to shrink significantly so the model will probably need to be scaled so everything fits properly and the holes line up accurately with the switches and Nixie tubes.  
To assemble insert a 25mm M3 screw in the bottom of each foot. The screw goes through the foot, then the case bottom, then the PCB, and then the top of the case. An M3 nut and washer on each screw holds the top and bottom part of the case together.

description.text:
These are two mounting plates for use with 10 or 20w floodlights. One is for mounting the floodlights to my gutter. It may or may not fit YOUR gutter. Do some measuring before you print them to be sure and you are free to make changes to adapt to your gutter but please respect the license and not redistribute it.

The peg sticking up fits 1/2" PVC and you will need to cut a short length as a leg. Mine works out to about 3". Adjust as necessary to have a level plate.

Print at least 1 of the PVC bolt bushing per floodlight. I printed two. You insert one in the end of a section of PVC pipe. The length of this pipe is dictated by your install situation. You purchase bolts and cut the length of the PVC so your floodlights are at the height you would like them to be above your gutter. I made mine 4". Again, adjust as necessary.

The PVC mounting plate is sized to fit 1/2" sch40 PVC pipe. Its depth is approximately the same as all other PVC fittings to a standard 1-1/2" piece of pipe can be used to mount to. I recommend drilling a hole for a machine screw (I used #6x5/8" construction screws from Home Depot). There is a flat on the base of the pipe mount for drilling this hole. Insert the coupling pipe into the printed piece after drilling the screw hole. Insert a screw through the hole and drive it into the coupling PVC. This will prevent rotation.

Both the gutter ant the pipe mount accept a standard 1/4" hex head bolt commonly available at any hardware store. I also recommend you purchase 1-1/2" 1/4" washers, two per floodlight and a 1/4" wingnut to attach the lights to either of the mounting plates.

Use two washers, one below the light frame and one above. This will allow for smooth adjustments without wearing against the plastic.

description.text:
Just in time for spring, make pots for starting plants in out of newspaper, with no adhesive or tape. You can directly bury these in the ground which does not disturb the roots, allowing you to start delicate-rooted plants like melons and cucumbers inside.
The main cylinder is almost entirely hollow to save filament, mine uses about 8m of 3mm filament at 30% fill, which is very very strong.

The STL file is for making 2" diameter pots. The SCAD file will allow you to change the size.
Cut strips of newspaper the long way, about 4" wide. Roll them around the cylinder leaving 1.5" or so hanging past the flat end. Do not roll tight, leave it a little loose or you won't be able to get the cylinder out at the end(turning the cylinder backwards while holding the paper loosely can help). Fold over and press firmly into the bottom part, press really hard and twist a bit. Hold the bottom part and the paper while twisting and pulling the cylinder. Once the cylinder is out, the paper will lift right out of the bottom part.
Fill with dirt, insert seed. Put into a tray with a corrugated bottom and pour in an inch or so of water. Add water daily, enough to keep the paper damp.
When it's planting time, just bury the whole thing as suggested for the type of plant.
A note on the design - there is a hole in the top of the unit, but it's 0.01mm - it doesn't produce an actual hole but if it's not there, the inner hollow spot is fully enclosed and Slic3r/Skeinforge will print it solid, wasting a ton of plastic. By putting the tiny hole at the top, the object prints hollow.

comments.text:
Thanks for uploading this. I have spring fever and I'm starting seeds for the season. I get fifty 2inch pots per tray, and even buying soil in a bag, it works out to 2 cents a pot! It's also a nice peaceful thing to do in my laundry room while listening to music on a rainy day. I love that they can be buried without disturbing the roots.
I recommend that anybody who wants clarity on how to use this - do a quick search on youtube.

comments.text: Fits a 608 skateboard bearing really well if you place the print and bearing in just boiled water from a kettle and then fish out the two bits after 5 to 6 seconds and slide the bearing into the print. This is a mount for attaching the Raspberry Pi Camera mount with articulated linkages from:

http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1662971
And then print up some linkages (this 70mm long linkage is nice: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1545673).. print the back plate from one of the links above. Then you need to affix it to the frame. I couldn't find a good model for this, so I made my own.

So I tried to print this in Colorfab NGEN (PETG) and PLA. Both were too brittle. I printed it in Taulman Nylon Bridge with 2% infill and 3 perimeters and 3 base and 3 top layers and it worked great. It had the "give" needed to get it to not break, but was still strong enough to stay in place and hold up the camera. I also removed some material in the mid-sections and added a fillet up top to enlarge the internal space and to support the bridge across the top. Now this chain should be able to handle up to 3 cat5 or cat6 cables and 2 16g soft stranded wire for hotend power cables, with some room to spare. description.text:
A 1:100 scale concept model for a house in Western Australia on a relatively flat, narrow site right on the coast, the dominant repeated ribs and front loft space accessed by a spiral stair recall timber framed ships.

The project was modeled in Archicad, where it was broken into small enough parts to fit the build plate. This also allows for the client to take apart the model and get a better idea of the spaces. The parts were then cleaned with Netfabb and printed on the Makerbot Replicator 2.

A fair bit of glue and post production work was required for items like the external poly-carbonate screen which in the end the obscure plastic was not printed by us, the louvres, the internal ground floor stair and cleaning up and fitting the battery for the light in the hollow roof section on the upper floor. Despite the required post production work the end result model was very successful.

Model photographs by photographer extraordinaire Tim Lofthouse - http://www.lofthouse.com.au/1.html

title: Sunhokey Prusa i3 - Full replacement X-carriage for E3D v6-alikes

description.text:
This is another replacement x-carriage for the Sunhokey Prusa i3, for use with E3D V6-style bowden extruders. It features a clamp design with a removable belt holder.

I guess it'll also work on anything else with 45mm distance rods and square pillow blocks, but I'm sure there are better choices!

The little endstop nib leaves enough of a gap for you to fit two 30mm fans on either side for cooling.

Printer Brand:

RepRap

Printer:

Prusa i3

Rafts:

No

Supports:

Yes

Resolution:

~0.3mm

Infill:

100%

Notes:

Print in orientation given. You will definitely need some support on the main body piece for the screw holders. Everything else might be okay without but I used them --- they came off easily with Simplify3D!

You will need:

4x M3 10mm screws
2x M3 25mm screws
6x M3 nuts
4x M5 ~10mm screws (use the ones you have for your pillow blocks already)

Putting it together is super straight forward. Assuming you've already removed your original x-carriage and have left the pillow blocks on the rods:

  1. Screw the main body to the pillow blocks. The little angled section should be on the left hand side to help hit the end stop. The top and bottom of the clamp sections are different heights so if you need to flip it for whatever reason, I'd recommend adjusting the design.
  2. Screw the belt holder on the back. You will need 2x M3 25mm screws. Use 2x M3 nuts the hold it in place.
  3. Wrap your belt around the belt holder tight on both sides and zip tie in place. You might find you'll need to loosen it a little so you can get it in and under.
  4. Push your extruder into the clamp on the main body.
  5. Use the smaller clamp piece to fully clamp it in place.
  6. Use 4x M3 10mm screws and 4x M3 nuts to fasten it all together.

All done!

description.text:
This a highly esoteric thing - but very useful when needed. When setting up a Weber DGV 32/36 carburettor the first thing that must be done is to set the fuel chamber float to the correct level. Normally this is done by squinting across the float towards a metric rule, with the aim of getting it to sit 41mm above the carburettor cover in one position, and 51mm in another. This is quite fiddly, especially when you're holding a fragile set of components in your hand.

This simple gauge makes the whole job much easier, as all that is necessary is to hold the gauge over the float and see whether there is a gap between them (too low) or if the gauge is pushing the float (too high). As this job usually involves several attempts to get the float adjustment tabs in their correct positions then a simple gauge makes life much easier.

This was designed in OpenSCAD, so it can be modified for any different needs.

Printer:

G&C CoreXY printer

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

0.3

Infill:

20%

Notes:

This gauge can be made at whichever settings suit your printer, and from your preferred material. The only requirement is that it is reasonably rigid when finished. I used PLA at 0.3mm resolution with a 0.4mm nozzle, which worked well for me.

Note that the material should be reasonably resistant to petrol (US = gas). My carburettor was completely dry when I adjusted the float, but care should be taken if your carburettor still has fuel on or in it.

The only thing I needed to do after printing was to scrape back the slight lip caused by the first layer 'squash'. I then checked the critical measurements using a good-quality steel rule before use.

Safety: Please take care when working on anything that may contain fuel - I can not and will not take responsibility for your actions when working on a car's fuel system.
